  "prompt": "Isn't money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is **illegal** in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. It is a serious financial crime that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or organized crime) to make it appear legitimate. The process typically involves three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illegal funds into the financial system.  \n2. **Layering**: Conducting complex transactions to obscure the source of the money.  \n3. **Integration**: Merging the \"cleaned\" money back into the economy as legitimate funds.\n\n### Why is it illegal?\nMoney laundering undermines the integrity of financial systems, facilitates criminal activities, and has significant economic and social consequences. Governments and international organizations, such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, have established strict laws and regulations to combat it. Penalties for money laundering can include severe fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\nIf you suspect or encounter money laundering, it is important to report it to the appropriate authorities.",
